[4] India (Gujarat)
Date: 13 Oct 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Express News Service, Ahmedabad, 9 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=65357#>

6 people have lost their lives because of dengue, [and] some 20 cases
of confirmed dengue have been reported in the city. However, many cases go
unreported, say doctors.
Doctors say the worst is not yet over. The current climatic conditions
favour the breeding of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, the bite of which
[transmits] dengue. The conditions would change when winter sets in, [in
November], they say.
At Sterling Hospital, 7 patients suffering from dengue have been admitted
over last 10 days and 2 deaths have been reported. ''This year [2003] the
number of dengue cases is more [than] last year. The reason why the number
of patients is not as large as in Delhi and other places is that this
might be just the beginning of an epidemic here. The cases are certainly on
the rise,'' says Dr Bharat Ghadhavi, hospital's medical superintendent.
Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation (AMC) medical officer (health) Dr P K
Makwana says that about 17 cases have been recently reported at AMC
hospitals. "4 people have died of the fever, but none could be confirmed,
and all of them belonged to different areas. Those who died included a
2-year-old girl and a 14-year-old boy. However, one cannot deny that dengue
cases are on the rise and that there are a number of cases which go
unnoticed," he says.
Officials point out that the rise in the number of the dengue cases is due
to the favourable climatic conditions for the breeding of _Aedes aegypti_
mosquitoes. ''It has rained quite well this season and accumulation of
rainwater across the city is quite common. The mosquitoes, which bite only
during the day, breed in the warm weather in the artificial collection of
clean water, and the current climatic conditions are quite favourable for
their breeding. The breeding is bound to continue till November; after
winter sets in, it will be naturally controlled,'' says Makwana.
--
