[5] India (nationwide)
Date: 13 Oct 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AFP Internet 9 Oct 2003 [edited]


80 dead, 4720 infected as India braces for severe dengue fever
--------------------------------------------------
Indian health authorities predicted a deadly wave of dengue fever, saying
80 people had died of the mosquito-borne disease in the past 3 months.
A National Anti Malaria Programme (NAMP) coordinator warned Thursday that
infections could rise because heavy monsoon rains have left stagnant pools
of water, which are breeding grounds for mosquitoes in overcrowded Indian
housing estates.
"At least 4720 cases of infection have been reported from 15 states, while
78 people have died of dengue up until 6 Oct 2003," said the NAMP official
who did not want to be identified.
Gujarat
---------
Another 2 people died of the disease Thursday in the western Indian state
of Gujarat taking the death toll to 80. "2 of my male patients died of
dengue. There are 7 other patients in my hospital being treated for the
same disease," said doctor Bharat Ghadvi at Gujarat's Sterling Hospital.
India this year [2003] had one of the wettest monsoons in 25 years, and
although the bountiful rains are expected to boost the agriculture-based
economy, they have caused floods and led to a spate of mosquito-borne
disease like malaria and dengue.
Kerala
--------
Dengue has reached alarming proportions in southern India, with the state
of Kerala recording 3155 cases of infection and 63 deaths, said the NAMP.
Karnataka
----------
Neighbouring Karnataka state has reported 6 deaths and 816 infections.
"There has been a lot of mixed infection such as dengue, typhoid, and
malaria," said Sudha Dinnakar, a doctor in Lakeside Hospital, in Bangalore,
the capital of Karnataka.
New Delhi
------------
New Delhi, home to 14 million people, has reported 568 cases of dengue
fever in recent months, with the disease claiming one life this week. The
Municipal Corporation of Delhi (MCD) has issued 15 541 notices this year
[2003] to owners with unclean residences and prosecuted 5114 cases as part
of a drive against dengue fever and malaria, deputy director B.K. Hazarika
said. Even Indian Law Minister Arun Jaitley and film superstar Amitabh
Bachchan were fined for having residences that could spread mosquito-borne
diseases.
